recalls.Summary: Volkswagen Group of America, Inc. (Audi) is recalling certain 2018-2019 Audi RS5 Coupe vehicles.  An incorrect positive battery terminal cover was installed.
recalls.Consequence: In the event of a rear crash, the incorrect cover can cause the 12-volt power supply to be compromised, preventing the vehicle doors from being opened from the outside, or the hazard warning lights from functioning, increasing risk of injury.
recalls.Remedy: Audi will notify owners, and dealers will replace the positive terminal cover, free of charge.  The recall began January 19, 2021.  Owners may contact Audi customer service at 1-800-253-2834.  Audi's number for this recall is 27i6.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Volkswagen Group of America, Inc. (Audi) is recalling certain 2017-2020 A4 Allroad, A4 Sedan, 2018-2019 RS5 Coupe, 2019 RS5 Sportback, 2018-2020 A5 Cabriolet, A5 Coupe, A5 Sportback, S4 Sedan, S5 Cabriolet, S5 Coupe, and Audi S5 Sportback vehicles.  The cable connecting the seat heater to the Passenger Occupant Detection System (PODS) may have a contact fault, causing the software to misdiagnose a malfunction and disable the passenger air bag.
recalls.Consequence: A disabled passenger air bag increases the risk of injury in the event of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will replace the connecting cable and either the heating mat or entire seat cover, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed January 7, 2022.  Owners may contact Audi customer service at 1-800-253-2834.  Audi's number for this recall is 74E3.  This recall is an expansion of Recall 19V-547 (74D9).  Vehicles previously repaired under 19V-547 will need to return for the new remedy.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.nhtsa.gov.

complaints.summary: Autonomous Emergency Services Notification Feature: Audi has informed its owners of vehicles made from 2018 and earlier that a safety feature provided as standard equipment in the vehicle will no longer be available because of the inevitable shut down of 3G wireless systems across North America. However, features that are not free (which require a subscription) are supported by a 4G radio in the car and will not be impacted. Owners were NEVER notified that two different wireless systems were used in the car, a 20 year old technology for safety related features, and a 4GLTE module for expensive, subscription based telematics which have nothing to do with safety. I purchased and selected my vehicle based on these exact safety systems, especially as I'm a disabled driver. I'm not even out of warranty yet and TWO features have now been or will about to be sunset, without a fix. I was also never notified that this was going to occur, I found out by accident and most dealers aren't even yet aware. Audi has stated they are working with an outside company to bandaid the issue, however, this bandaid was not integrated with the car and basically won't solve the problem that it isn't the car I purchased. In the posted letters other owners received, there is ZERO indication of when this might be available, no evidence or indication it will be approved by the DOT or NHTSA because it's a bandaid. I have already contacted Audi for resolution, without result. I have requested updates, without result. The process is supposed to take 20 business days. It has now been over 40 business days. Regardless of the price of the vehicle, there was NEVER any indication by the dealer or in the manual that would lead customers to believe two different technologies were in use in the car.... 4G is plastered everywhere, however, 3G is stated nowhere. In hindsight, this is not only a dangerous situation for many drivers, but also a fraudulent one. Need help.

issues.title: Carbon Buildup in Direct Injection Engine
issues.description: The 2.9L TFSI V6 engine suffers from carbon buildup on intake valves due to direct injection design, causing reduced performance and rough idling
issues.fix_description: Walnut blasting intake valves to remove carbon deposits, typically required every 40,000-60,000 miles
issues.prevention: Use top-tier gasoline, drive highway speeds regularly, consider periodic intake cleaning services

issues.title: Thermostat Failure
issues.description: Thermostat housing develops leaks or the thermostat itself fails, causing coolant loss and potential overheating issues
issues.fix_description: Replace thermostat and housing assembly, refill coolant system and bleed air
issues.prevention: Regular coolant system maintenance, check coolant levels regularly

issues.title: Oil Cooler Line Leaks
issues.description: Oil cooler lines develop leaks at connection points, leading to oil loss and potential engine damage if not addressed
issues.fix_description: Replace oil cooler lines and seals, may require engine cover removal
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, monitor oil levels frequently

issues.title: Turbocharger Wastegate Rattle
issues.description: Turbocharger wastegate actuators develop play causing rattling noise, particularly noticeable at idle and low RPM
issues.fix_description: Replace turbocharger wastegate actuators or entire turbocharger assembly
issues.prevention: Use quality oil, follow service intervals, avoid extended idle periods

issues.title: Infotainment System Freezing
issues.description: MMI infotainment system experiences random freezing, slow response, or complete failure requiring restart
issues.fix_description: Software updates, module reset, or replacement of MMI unit in severe cases
issues.prevention: Keep software updated, avoid extreme temperatures

issues.title: Differential Oil Leak
issues.description: Rear differential develops oil leaks from seals, particularly common in Quattro all-wheel drive models
symptoms: oil spots under rear of car
issues.fix_description: Replace differential seals and refill with proper specification oil
issues.prevention: Regular differential service, avoid aggressive launches

issues.title: Water Pump Failure
issues.description: Electric water pump fails prematurely causing coolant circulation issues and potential engine overheating
issues.fix_description: Replace electric water pump and related components, system flush and refill
issues.prevention: Regular coolant changes, address cooling system issues promptly

issues.title: Fuel Injector Carbon Fouling
issues.description: High-pressure fuel injectors become fouled with carbon deposits, causing misfires and rough running
issues.fix_description: Clean or replace fuel injectors, may require intake manifold removal
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, periodic fuel system cleaning services

issues.title: Brake Pad Premature Wear
issues.description: Performance brake pads wear faster than expected, particularly on front axle due to aggressive compound and driving conditions
issues.fix_description: Replace brake pads and resurface or replace rotors if necessary
issues.prevention: Avoid aggressive braking, regular brake inspections

issues.title: Suspension Strut Mount Noise
issues.description: Front strut mounts develop noise over bumps and during steering inputs due to worn bushings
issues.fix_description: Replace strut mount assemblies and associated bushings
issues.prevention: Avoid potholes and harsh impacts, regular suspension inspection

editorial.tagline: Twin-turbo fury wrapped in Teutonic precision
editorial.hero_blurb: The RS5 B9 represents Audi's masterful evolution from naturally aspirated theater to turbocharged efficiency without sacrificing soul. This grand touring weapon delivers supercar acceleration wrapped in daily-drivable sophistication.
editorial.essence: The B9 RS5 brilliantly balances explosive twin-turbo performance with refined all-weather capability. It's a thinking enthusiast's choice that prioritizes usable power delivery over raw drama.
editorial.heritage: Born from Audi's quattro rally DNA, the RS5 nameplate emerged in 2010 as the brand's answer to BMW's M3. The B9 generation marked a controversial but ultimately successful transition from the beloved naturally aspirated V8 to forced induction efficiency.
editorial.design_philosophy: Understated aggression defines the RS5's aesthetic - wide haunches, functional aero, and signature honeycomb grilles hint at performance without screaming for attention. The interior blends luxury with purposeful sport-focused ergonomics.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not a direct racing derivative, the RS5 carries Audi's DTM touring car experience and Le Mans endurance racing knowledge in its advanced quattro system and aerodynamic development.
editorial.engine_character: The 2.9L twin-turbo V6 delivers immediate, crushing torque from just 1900 RPM with minimal lag. It's clinical in its efficiency but lacks the theatrical crescendo of its V8 predecessor, trading drama for devastating real-world performance.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 8-speed tiptronic shifts with Germanic precision in auto mode and responds crisply to manual inputs, though it prioritizes smoothness over the aggressive slam of a dual-clutch setup.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Planted and confidence-inspiring thanks to quattro all-wheel drive, the RS5 rotates willingly when provoked but remains fundamentally stable. The adaptive dampers offer genuine versatility between comfort and track focus.
editorial.steering_feel: Electrically assisted steering provides good weighting and decent feedback, though it lacks the ultimate precision and communication of the best driver's cars. It's accurate and confidence-inspiring rather than truly engaging.
editorial.brake_confidence: Massive brakes deliver exceptional stopping power with good pedal feel and fade resistance. The system inspires confidence for spirited driving while remaining progressive for daily use.
editorial.sound_signature: A deep, cultured growl with artificial enhancement that's convincing enough to satisfy most ears. The exhaust note is more sophisticated than exciting, with sport mode adding welcome aggression without becoming obnoxious.
editorial.ideal_owner: Successful professionals who want supercar performance in a refined, weather-independent package that won't draw unwanted attention or compromise daily usability.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Purists seeking maximum driver engagement, badge snobs who demand German luxury prestige, or enthusiasts prioritizing raw emotional connection over clinical efficiency.
editorial.buyers_summary: Focus on 2020+ models for the latest infotainment and avoid early production cars. The RS5 excels as a daily-driven performance car but may disappoint those seeking maximum driving thrills.

SETTING: Private collector's industrial warehouse garage. Brick warehouse with arched windows OR modern concrete gallery OR vintage factory with timber beams.

COMPOSITION: Front 3/4 hero angle showing front fascia and driver's side profile. Show COMPLETE car (all four wheels, both bumpers, full roofline). Camera at knee height.

LIGHTING: Golden hour sunlight streaming through large industrial windows. Warm color temperature. Cinematic depth.

TECHNICAL: Magazine-quality automotive photography. Photorealistic, no CGI look. No people, no text, no watermarks, no logos, no license plates.
